				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">A CPU can be made with only one instruction (one kind is the &quot;TOGA computer&quot;, which is mainly just a programmable counter and a gate), although it is generally useful to have more. Many instruction sets do not have status flags, such as MMIX (branch instructions check if a given register is zero, nonzero, positive, negative, even, odd, whatever). (It would also be helpful to specify what ALU instructions.) On some instruction sets (such as VAX), the program counter is just another register; you can do stuff with it like with any other register. Fully orthogonal is good. (I happen to like MMIX.)</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="gopher://zzo38computer.org/" class="postlink">.</a></div>
					<br clear="all" /><br />

